 {  
    "response_text": "Over the 100-year simulation period, the mean household initial risk attitude exhibits no temporal variation, maintaining constant values from the initial timestep through the final observation. The metric spans a range from approximately -0.11 to +0.18 across the population of social learning agents, with individual households maintaining distinct, static risk disposition values throughout the duration. These constant values represent the fixed baseline attitudes toward uncertainty that social learning agents possess when interpreting pasture conditions and neighbor performance at the outset. The distribution indicates substantial heterogeneity in initial risk profiles among these agents, with specific values observed at discrete levels including approximately 0.18, 0.14, 0.12, 0.11, 0.08, 0.07, 0.05, 0.01, and 0.00, as well as negative values including approximately -0.01, -0.03, -0.05, -0.07, -0.09, and -0.11. Because these values reflect initial conditions that do not evolve under the single-loop learning configuration, they persist unchanged across all 100 steps, providing stable individual reference points for stocking decisions regardless of accumulated experience or environmental feedback."  
}

